To implement this functionality, we'll create a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word. Here's an example implementation:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>
#include <sstream>

int main() {
    // Open the input file
    std::ifstream input_file("input.txt");
    if (!input_file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error: Could not open input file." << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Read the word to search for from the command line or standard input
    std::cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
    std::string search_word;
    std::getline(std::cin, search_word);

    // Initialize a map to store the word count
    std::map<std::string, int> word_count;

    // Read each line of the input file and update the word count
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(input_file, line)) {
        std::stringstream ss(line);
        std::string token;
        int count = 0;
        while (ss >> token) {
            if (token == search_word) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        // Update the word count map for each line
        for (const auto& kv : word_count) {
            if (line.find(kv.first) != std::string::npos) {
                kv.second += count; // update the word count for this line as well as any previous occurrences in the file
            }
        }
        // Add the word count for this line only (excluding previous occurrences)
        word_count[line] = count;
    }

    // Print the final word count map
    for (const auto& kv : word_count) {
        std::cout << kv.first << ": " << kv.second << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

In this implementation, we first open the input file and read the word to search for from either the command line or standard input. We then initialize a map to store the word count, and read each line of the input file. For each line, we convert it to a stringstream and iterate through each token, updating the word count for any matches of the search word. We also update the word count map for each line by checking if the line contains any previous occurrences of the search word using `find()`. Finally, we print the final word count map. Note that this implementation assumes that there are no leading/trailing whitespace in either the input file or search word.

To implement a queue using two stacks, we will use a technique called "stack-as-queue" or "double-ended stack".

The idea is to have two stacks: one for enqueueing elements and the other for dequeuing elements. When we want to enqueue an element, we push it onto the first stack (let's call it `stack1`). When we want to dequeue an element, we check if the second stack (let's call it `stack2`) is empty. If it is, we pop all elements from `stack1` and push them onto `stack2` to ensure that the element at the top of `stack1` is the next element to be dequeued. If `stack2` is not empty, we simply pop the element from the top of `stack2`.

Here's the implementation in Python:

```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.stack1 = []
        self.stack2 = []

    def enqueue(self, item):
        self.stack1.append(item)

    def dequeue(self):
        if len(self.stack2) == 0:
            while len(self.stack1) > 0:
                self.stack2.append(self.stack1.pop())
        return self.stack2.pop()

    def is_empty(self):
        return len(self.stack1) == 0 and len(self.stack2) == 0
```

The `is_empty` method checks if both stacks are empty, since we can only dequeue from a non-empty stack.
